President Donald J. Trump and Prime Minister Shinzo Abe of Japan met in New York to discuss the ongoing threat posed by North Korea. They agreed that North Korea's recent missile launches and nuclear test are a grave threat to international peace. Trump reassured Abe of the United States' commitment to defend Japan using its military capabilities, and both leaders reaffirmed their solidarity. They welcomed the adoption of UN Security Council Resolution 2375 and pledged to work with South Korea and the international community to ensure its full implementation. Trump and Abe also discussed economic matters and expressed their commitment to strengthening the partnership between their countries. They concluded by affirming their continued coordination in preparation for Trump's upcoming visit to Japan.